SIMPLE: incubator
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incubator
<hw>In"cu*ba`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That
which incubates, especially, an apparatus by means of which eggs are
hatched by artificial heat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An apparatus containing an enclosed chamber, used
for the cultivation of micro⟦oum⟧rganisms or tissue cultures by
maintaining a suitable temperature and atmospheric composition. Some
incubators have no provision for maintaining a special atmosphere, while
in others, especially for anaerobic organisms and tissue culture, the
moisture level and composition of the gases are also
controlled.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An apparatus consisting of
enclosed chamber, for maintaining prematurely born babies in a favorable
environment until able to thrive under normal conditions. The
temperature and level of oxygen in the atmosphere may be
controlled.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incubatory</ent>⟦br⟧
